# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anti-consumerism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] From April through June 1919, a series of bombings were carried out or attempted across the United States by Galleanists (followers of Italian insurrectionary anarchist Luigi Galleani).
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The targets included anti-immigration politicians, anti-anarchist officials, and prominent businessmen, as well as a journalist and a church.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Almost all of the bombs were sent by mail.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The bombings were one of the major factors contributing to the First Red Scare.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Two people were killed, including one of the bombers, and two injured.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] In late April 1919, at least 36 booby trap dynamite-filled bombs were mailed to a cross-section of prominent politicians and appointees, including the Attorney General as well as justice officials, newspaper editors and businessmen, including John D.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The mail bombs were wrapped in brown paper with similar address and advertising labels.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Inside, wrapped in bright green paper and stamped "Gimbel Brothers-Novelty Samples", was a cardboard box with a 6 by 3 by 1 inch (150 by 80 by 30 mm) block of hollowed wood, packed with a stick of dynamite.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] A small vial of sulfuric acid was fastened to the wood block, along with three fulminate-of-mercury blasting caps.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Opening one end of the box (the end marked "open") released a coil spring that caused the acid to drip from its vial onto the blasting caps; the acid ate through the caps, igniting them and detonating the dynamite.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The Galleanists intended their bombs to be delivered on May Day.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Since 1890 and the Second International, May 1 had been celebrated as the international day of communist, anarchist and socialist revolutionary solidarity.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Seattle Mayor Ole Hanson, who had recently attained national prominence for opposing a general strike in Seattle, received one of the mailed package bombs, but it was opened by William Langer, a member of his office staff.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Langer opened the wrong end of the box and the bottle of acid dropped onto a table without detonation.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] He took the bomb to the local police, who notified the Post Service and other police agencies.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Hardwick, who had co-sponsored the Alien Anarchists Exclusion Act of 1918, received a similarly disguised bomb.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] It blew off the hands of his housekeeper when she attempted to open the package.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The senator's wife was also injured in the blast, which severely burned her face and neck and a piece of shrapnel cut her lip and loosened several of her teeth.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] News reports of the Hardwick bomb described its distinctive packaging and an alert post office employee in New York connected this to 16 similar packages which he had set aside a few days earlier for insufficient postage.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Another 12 bombs were eventually recovered before reaching their intended targets.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] On the evening of June 2, 1919, the Galleanists managed to detonate nine large bombs nearly simultaneously in eight cities.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] These bombs were much larger than those sent in April, using up to 25 pounds (11 kg) of dynamite and all were wrapped or packaged with heavy metal slugs designed to act as shrapnel.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Addressees included government officials who had endorsed anti-sedition laws and deportation of immigrants suspected of crimes or associated with illegal movements, as well as judges who had sentenced anarchists to prison.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Palmer, who had already been the recipient of a mail bomb in April, was again attacked in the new wave of violence.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Though not seriously injured, Palmer and his family were shaken by the blast and the house itself was largely demolished.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Two near-casualties of the same bomb were Assistant Secretary of the Navy Franklin Delano Roosevelt and his wife Eleanor, then living across the street from Palmer.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] They had passed the house just minutes before the explosion and their residence was close enough that one of the bomber's body parts landed on their doorstep.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The flyer was later traced to a print shop operated by two anarchists, typesetter Andrea Salsedo and compositor Roberto Elia, who were both Galleanists according to the later memoirs of other members.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Salsedo died under suspicious circumstances (either by suicide or defenestration depending on the source) was and Elia refused an offer to cancel deportation proceedings if he would testify about his role in the Galleanist organization.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Unable to secure enough evidence for criminal trials, authorities continued to use the Anarchist Exclusion Act and related statutes to deport known Galleanists.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Fueled by labor unrest and the anarchist bombings, and then spurred on by Attorney General A.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Mitchell Palmer's attempt to suppress radical and non-radical labor organizations, the response to the bombings was characterized by exaggerated rhetoric, illegal search and seizures, unwarranted arrests and detentions and the deportation of several hundred suspected radicals and anarchists.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Palmer, twice targeted by anarchist bombs, organized the nationwide series of police actions known as the Palmer raids in November 1919 and January 1920.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Under suspicion of violating the Espionage Act, the Sedition Act and/or the Immigration Act of 1918, approximately 10,000 people were arrested, of whom 3,500 were held in detention.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] Of those held in detention, 556 resident aliens were eventually deported.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The bombings were dramatized in the 2012 film *No God, No Master.* The bombing of the home of Palmer was also dramatized in the 2011 film *J.
[src:anti-consumerism/1919-united-states-anarchist-bombings] The June Bombings and the "Plain Words" fliers were referenced in the video game *Arkham Origins* by Anarky, one of the game's antagonists.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The Conference was to be the launch of a new millennial round of trade negotiations.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The negotiations were quickly overshadowed by massive street protests outside the hotels and the Washington State Convention and Trade Center.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The protests were nicknamed "**N30**", akin to J18 and similar mobilizations.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The protests marked the reappearance of anarchism as a significant force within the Western far left, influenced subsequent social movements by spreading the black bloc strategy and drew widespread international attention to the anti-globalization movement.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Locally, they led to the resignation of Norm Stamper, Seattle's police chief.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] From the 1970s onward, and even more so following the fall of the USSR and the 1990s, the anarchist movement underwent a rebirth in the West.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The anti-globalization movement formed during the same period and was influenced by the anarchists who joined it from the very beginning.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Although not all anti-globalists were anarchists, the two movements largely converged; this resulted in the anti-globalization movement adopting anarchist political procedures and practices.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Previous mass demonstrations had taken place in Australia in December 1997, in which newly formed grass-roots organizations blockaded Melbourne, Perth, Sydney, and Darwin city centers.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Planning for the actions began months in advance and included local, national, and international organizations.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The protests also drew support from some political conservatives, such as American presidential candidate and commentator Pat Buchanan.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The coalition was loose, with some opponent groups focused on opposition to WTO policies (especially those related to free trade), with others motivated by prolabor, anticapitalist, or environmental agendas.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Many of the NGOs represented at the protests came with credentials to participate in the official meetings, while also planning various educational and press events.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The AFL–CIO, with cooperation from its member unions, organized a large permitted rally and march from Seattle Center to downtown.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] However, others were more interested in taking direct action, including both civil disobedience and acts of vandalism and property destruction to disrupt the meeting.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Several groups were loosely organized together under the Direct Action Network (DAN), with a plan to disrupt the meetings by blocking streets and intersections downtown to prevent delegates from reaching the convention center, where the meeting was to be held.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The black bloc was not affiliated with DAN, but was responding to the original call for autonomous resistance actions on November 30 issued by People's Global Action.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Of the different coalitions that aligned in protest were the "teamsters and turtles" – a blue–green alliance consisting of the teamsters (trade unions) and environmentalists.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Certain activists, including locals and an additional group of anarchists from Eugene, Oregon (where they had gathered that summer for a music festival), advocated more confrontational tactics, and conducted vandalism of corporate properties in downtown Seattle.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] In a subsequent communique, they listed the particular corporations targeted, which they considered to have committed corporate crime.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] On July 12, the *Financial Times* reported that the latest United Nations Human Development report advocated "principles of performance for multinationals on labour standards, fair trade and environmental protection ... needed to counter the negative effects of globalisation on the poorest nations".
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The report itself argued, "An essential aspect of global governance is responsibility to people—to equity, to justice, to enlarging the choices of all".
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] On July 16, Helene Cooper of *The Wall Street Journal* warned of an impending "massive mobilization against globalization" being planned for the end-of-year Seattle WTO conference.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Activists staged a spoof of Seattle daily newspaper the *Post-Intelligencer* on Wednesday November 24, inserting thousands of hoax editions of a four-page front-page wrap-around into piles of newspapers awaiting distribution to hundreds of street boxes and retail outlets.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The spoof front-page stories were "Boeing to move overseas" (to Indonesia) and "Clinton pledges help for poorest nations".
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The byline on the Boeing story attributed it to Joe Hill (a union organizer who had been executed by firing squad in Utah in 1915).
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] On the morning of Tuesday, November 30, 1999, the DAN's plan was put into effect.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Several hundred activists arrived in the deserted streets near the convention center and began to take control of key intersections.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Over the next few hours, a number of marchers began to converge on the area from different directions.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Some demonstrators held rallies, others held teach-ins and at least one group staged an early-morning street party.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Meanwhile, a number of protesters still controlled the intersections using lockdown formations.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] That morning, the King County Sheriff's Office and Seattle Police Department fired pepper spray, tear gas canisters, and stun grenades at protesters at several intersections in an attempt to reopen the blocked streets and allow as many WTO delegates as possible through the blockade.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] At 6th Avenue and Union Street, the crowd threw objects back at the police.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] By late morning, the black bloc had swelled to 200 people and smashed dozens of shops and police cars.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] This seems to have set off a chain reaction of sorts, with previously nonviolent protesters throwing bottles at police and joining in the vandalism shortly before noon.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The police were eventually overwhelmed by the mass of protesters downtown, including many who had chained themselves together and were blocking intersections.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Meanwhile, the late-morning labor-organized rally and march drew tens of thousands; though the intended march route had them turning back before they reached the convention center, some ignored the marshals and joined what had become a chaotic scene downtown.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] At noon, the opening ceremony at the convention center was officially canceled.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] It took police much of the afternoon and evening to clear the streets.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Overnight, the governor of Washington, Gary Locke, called in two battalions of Army National Guardsmen, other law enforcement agencies sent support, and before daylight on Wednesday, troops and officers lined the perimeter of the no-protest zone.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Police surrounded and arrested several groups of would-be protesters (and more than one bystander).
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Beginning at 21:00, a major clash took place on Broadway in the vicinity of Denny Way, involving rocks, bottles, and police concussion grenades.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] It did not involve a black bloc, but appears to have included local residents, although it is known that many local residents were treated as protesters, even being teargassed, despite having no part in the protests.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Police called in from other cities mistook the typically crowded streets of Capitol Hill as groups of protesters.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] More than 500 people were jailed on Wednesday.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Throughout the day, police used tear gas to disperse crowds downtown, although a permitted demonstration organized by the Steelworkers Union was held along the waterfront.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Thousands demonstrated outside the Seattle Police Department protesting their tactics and arrests of peaceful protestors.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] President Clinton arrived and attended the conference.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] On December 3 the conference ended as delegations were unable to reach agreements, partly in response to the protests.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Confrontations with the police continued, albeit at a lower intensity.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The primary goal of disrupting the trade talks achieved, some sought the horizons of possibility; it was determined quickly that the necessary ambition to achieve the broader goals of various anarchist factions was not sufficient.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] An article in the magazine *The Nation* disputed that Molotov cocktails have ever been thrown at an antiglobalization protest within the United States.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Media coverage of the protests condemned the violence of some of the protesters, particularly anarchists, who carried out "symbolic" acts of property damage.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Though many denounced the violent tactics used by protesters, this violence resulted in increased media coverage of the event.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The WTO meeting had an increase in evening news airtime from 10 minutes and 40 seconds on the first day of the meeting to 17 minutes on the first day of violence.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] In addition, WTO coverage was the lead or second story on CNN, ABC, CBS, and NBC after violence was reported.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Two days after the start of violence, the meeting remained the top story on three of the four networks.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] This coverage did not center exclusively on the violence.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Instead, details of the protesters' message and antiglobalization campaign were included along with the discussions of symbolic violence taking place.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] DeLuca and Peeples reported that the violence served as a "dense surface" that opened viewers' and readers' minds to a whole new way of thinking about globalization and corporations' operations.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] To many in North American anarchist and radical circles, the Seattle WTO riots, protests, and demonstrations were viewed as a success.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Prior to the "Battle of Seattle", almost no mention was made of "antiglobalization" in the US media, while the protests were seen as having forced the media to report on 'why' anybody would oppose the WTO.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] While anarchism was already reconstituting and growing in the United States in the years leading up to the Seattle protests, this event thrusted the political movement back onto the national and international political and media stage.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] According to historian Spencer Beswick, the media at the time focused on the role played by black blocs without realizing the underlying and central work anarchists performed to organize the protests and mobilize the population.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The black bloc strategy, which predated the Seattle protests, gained new significance following the event.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] It was subsequently adopted and exported, a similar protest occurred in Prague in September 2000.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Around 12,000 activists gathered to protest during the International Monetary Fund and World Bank summit on September 27, 2000.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The black bloc strategy was notably replicated later during the 2001 G8 riots in Genoa.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] Controversy over the city's response to the protests resulted in the resignation of the police chief of Seattle, Norm Stamper, and arguably played a role in Schell's loss to Greg Nickels in the 2001 mayoral primary election.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] The massive size of the protest added $3 million to the city's estimated meeting budget of $6 million, partly due to city cleanup and police overtime bills.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] In addition, the damage to commercial businesses from vandalism and lost sales has been estimated at $20 million.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] On January 16, 2004, the city of Seattle settled with 157 individuals arrested outside of the no-protest zone during the WTO events, agreeing to pay them a total of $250,000.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] On January 30, 2007, a federal jury found that the city had violated protesters' Fourth Amendment constitutional rights by arresting them without probable cause or evidence.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] An Ipsos poll taken in the aftermath of the protests indicated that they had little impact on public perception of the WTO within the United States.
[src:anti-consumerism/1999-seattle-wto-protests] 19% of respondents said that the protests made them more opposed to the WTO, 11% said the protests made them support the WTO more, and 67% said the protests had no effect on their opinion.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The 350 in the name stands for 350 parts per million (ppm) of carbon dioxide (CO2), which has been identified as a safe upper limit to avoid a climate tipping point.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] By the end of 2007, the year 350.org was founded, atmospheric CO2 had already exceeded this threshold, reaching 383 ppm CO2; as of July 2022, the concentration had reached 421 ppm CO2, a level 50% higher than pre-industrial levels.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Through online campaigns, grassroots organizing, mass public actions, and collaboration with an extensive network of partner groups and organizations, 350.org mobilized thousands of volunteer organizers in over 188 countries.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] It was one of the many organizers of the September 2019 Global Climate Strike, which evolved from the Fridays for Future movement.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org runs a variety of campaigns, from the local to the global scale.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The fossil fuel divestment campaign, also known as "Fossil Free", borrows activist tactics from other social movements, notably the successful campaign for disinvestment from South Africa over apartheid.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] From its inception in 2012 through October 2021, over 1500 institutions with more than US$40.43 trillion in assets under management had committed to divest from fossil fuels.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The campaign has grown from colleges and universities around the United States to now include other kinds of public and private institutions, such as the City of New York, major Japanese banks, development banks, religious institutions, and more.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Campaigns for divestment are active and growing around the world.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] From 2013 to 2020, Australian members built a network of local groups across the country advocating for institutions to divest.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org named the Keystone XL pipeline as a critical issue and turning point for the environmental movement, as well as for then-President Barack Obama's legacy.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] NASA climatologist James Hansen labeled the Keystone XL pipeline as "game over" for the planet and called the amount of carbon stored in Canadian bitumen sands a "fuse to the largest carbon bomb on the planet".
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org cited oil spills along the proposed pipeline route, which would pass near Texas' Carrizo-Wilcox Aquifer, which supplies drinking water to more than 12 million people, as one important reason to reject the pipeline.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] They argued that it could also pose a danger to the Ogallala Aquifer, the largest aquifer in western North America that supplies drinking water and irrigation to millions of people and agricultural businesses.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org has opposed the economic argument that has been made by proponents of the pipeline, arguing that Keystone XL would create only a few thousand temporary jobs during construction.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The State Department estimated that ultimately the pipeline will create 35 permanent jobs.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Additionally, the Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC) has said that the Keystone XL pipeline will increase gas prices instead of lowering them as oil industry proponents claimed.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The NRDC's study also rebutted the claim that the pipeline will lead to energy independence because the pipeline would carry tar sands from Canada to Texas for export to the global market.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Partly due to efforts from 350.org and other organizations, President Obama officially rejected the building of Keystone XL on November 6, 2015.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] This marked the end of a seven-year review of the pipeline.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Speaking on the decision, Bill McKibben said, "President Obama is the first world leader to reject a project because of its effect on the climate.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] In response, proponent TC Energy filed a US$15 billion lawsuit under NAFTA's Chapter 11.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] On January 24, 2017, President Donald Trump took action intended to permit the pipeline's completion, whereupon TC Energy suspended their NAFTA Chapter 11 action.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] On January 18, 2018, TransCanada Pipelines (now TC PipeLines) announced they had secured commitments from oil companies to ship 500,000 barrels (79,000 m3) of dilbit per day for 20 years, meeting the threshold to make the project economically viable.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] On January 20, 2021, President Joe Biden revoked the permit for the pipeline on his first day in office.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] On June 9, 2021, the project was abandoned by TC Energy.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] In its coverage of the abandonment, *The Wall Street Journal* highlighted the role of 350.org in the project's failure.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Local campaigns in jurisdictions around the world have passed laws limiting or banning fossil fuel production.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] These include 410 municipal bans for fracking in Brazil and two state bans: Santa Catarina and Paraná.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] An "International Day of Climate Action" on October 24, 2009, was organized by 350.org to influence the delegates going to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change meeting in December 2009 (COP15).
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] This was the first global campaign ever organized around a scientific data point.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The group reported that they organized the world's "most widespread day of political action" on that Saturday, reporting 5,245 actions in 181 countries.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] As a follow-up to 2009's International Day of Climate Action, 350.org and the 10:10 Climate Campaign joined forces to help coordinate another global day of action, which occurred on October 10, 2010.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The 2010 campaign was focused on concrete actions that can be taken locally to help combat climate change.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Actions from tree-plantings to solar panel installations to huge electricity service-provider switching parties occurred in almost every country around the world.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The organization's efforts continued into 2012 with a planned May 5 worldwide series of rallies under the slogan "Connect the Dots" to draw attention to the links between climate change and extreme weather.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Per the 350.org website, the day is called "Climate Impacts Day".
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Phase 1 of Global Power Shift was a convergence in Istanbul, Turkey, in June 2013 of about five-hundred climate organizers from 135 countries.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Phase 2 of Global Power Shift involves the organizers who were in Turkey in June 2013 to bring home what they learned to organize summits, events, and mobilizations.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org launched the Summer Heat campaign in the summer of 2013, a wave of mass mobilizations across the USA.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Summer Heat actions took place at eleven locations: Richmond, California; Vancouver, Washington; Green River, Utah; Albuquerque, New Mexico; Houston, Texas; St.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Ignace, Michigan; Warren, Ohio; Washington, D.C.; Camp David, Maryland; Somerset, Massachusetts; and Sebago Lake, Maine.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Participants included grassroots organizers, labor unions, farmers, ranchers, environmental justice groups, and others.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org helped organize the People's Climate March, which took place on September 21, 2014.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 2,000 events took place around the world.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org was one of the leading organizers of the Global Climate Strike, September 20–27, 2019.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Strike actions were planned in more than 150 countries.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Worn by a broad coalition of NGOs, unions, and social movements, the strikes were inspired by the school strikes of the Fridays for Future movement.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Also supported is the digital climate strike, which calls for a shutdown or 'go green' of websites with redirection to coverage of the physical mobilizations.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The aim of the Global Climate Strike was to draw attention to the emergency climate crisis and to create pressure on politics, the media and the fossil fuel industry.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The strikes were intended as a prelude to a permanent mass mobilization.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Over 7.6 million people across 185 countries participated in the mass mobilization event, making the Global Climate Strike the largest climate mobilization in history.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Apart from special events, 350.org organizes actions on an ongoing basis to promote its message.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] In December 2009, the group petitioned the United States Environmental Protection Agency to set national limits for greenhouse gases using the Clean Air Act, asking the agency to cap atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide at 350 parts per million.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The organization created and distributed a time-lapse video showing the recent retreat of Mendenhall Glacier in Alaska, graphically depicting the impacts of warming climates.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The *Do The Math* movie is a 42-minute documentary film about the rising movement to change the terrifying math of the climate crisis and challenge the fossil fuel industry.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The math revolves around these three numbers: to stay below 2 degrees Celsius of global warming we can emit only 565 more gigatons of carbon dioxide versus the 2,795 gigatons held in proven reserves by fossil fuel corporations.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] This warming rise was agreed to in the 2009 Copenhagen Summit as a limit.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] "Rise: From One Island to Another" is a poem and video project that showcases the impacts of sea level rise and the ways the climate crisis spans across national borders.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The poem is written by two islanders, Kathy Jetn̄il-Kijiner from the Marshall Islands and Aka Niviâna from Greenland.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Through their poetry, they draw connections between their realities of melting glaciers and rising sea levels.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org founder Bill McKibben writes that "[climate change] science is uncontroversial.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] But science alone can't make change, because it appeals only to the hemisphere of the brain that values logic and reason.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The "Rise" film project team included photographer and photojournalist Dan Lin, freelance filmmaker Nick Stone, visual storyteller Rob Lau, and filmmaker Oz Go.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org was founded by American environmentalist Bill McKibben and a group of students from Middlebury College in Vermont.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Their 2007 "Step It Up" campaign involved 1,400 demonstrations at famous sites across the United States.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] McKibben credits these activities with making Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama change their energy policies during the 2008 United States presidential campaign.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Starting in 2008, 350.org built upon the "Step It Up" campaign and made it into a global organization.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] McKibben is an American environmentalist and writer who wrote one of the first books on global warming for the general public, and frequently writes about climate change, alternative energy, and the need for more localized economies.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] As of 2022, McKibben was a senior advisor to 350.org and May Boeve is the Executive Director.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Rajendra Pachauri, the UN's "top climate scientist" and leader of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), has come out, as have others, in favor of reducing atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide to 350 ppm.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] McKibben called news of Pachauri's embrace of the 350 ppm target "amazing".
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Some media have indicated that Pachauri's endorsement of the 350 ppm target was a victory for 350.org's activism.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] The organization had a lift in prominence after McKibben appeared on *The Colbert Report* television show on August 17, 2009.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] McKibben promotes the organization on speaking tours and by writing articles about it for many major newspapers and media, such as the *Los Angeles Times* and *The Guardian*.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] In 2012, the organization was presented with the Katerva Award for Behavioural Change.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] NASA climate scientist James Hansen contended that any atmospheric concentration of carbon dioxide (CO2) above 350 parts per million (ppm) was unsafe.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Carbon dioxide, the main greenhouse gas, rose by 2.6 ppm to 396 ppm in 2013 from the previous year (annual global averages).
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] In May 2013, two independent teams of scientists measuring CO2 near the summit of Mauna Loa in Hawaii recorded that the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere exceeded 400 ppm, probably for the first time in more than 3 million years of Earth history.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] It crossed 415 ppm in May 2019 and the amount continues to rise.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 2 °C (3.6 °F) was agreed upon during the 2009 Copenhagen Accord as a limit for global temperature rise.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] In the 2015 Paris Agreement, 1.5 °C of warming was introduced as a limit, reflecting the significant difference in impacts between 2 °C and 1.5 °C, especially for climate-vulnerable areas.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] This was reaffirmed in the 2018 report by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, where the world's leading scientists urged action to limit warming to 1.5 °C.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] In order to stay below a 2 °C increase, scientists have estimated that humans can pour roughly 565 more gigatons of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Fossil-fuel companies have about 2,795 gigatons of carbon already contained in their proven coal and oil and gas reserves, and is the amount of fossil fuels they are currently planning to burn.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 2,795 gigatons is five times higher than the limit of 565 gigatons that would keep Earth under a global temperature increase of 2 °C, which is already unsafe according to the latest science.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] 350.org claims alliance with 300 organizations around the world.
[src:anti-consumerism/350-org] Many notable figures have publicly allied themselves with the organization or its goal to spread the movement, including Archbishop Desmond Tutu, Alex Steffen, Bianca Jagger, David Suzuki, and Colin Beavan.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] "**A las Barricadas**" (English: To the Barricades) is a Spanish anarchist anthem, popularised during the Spanish Civil War as the official hymn of the National Confederation of Labour (CNT).
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] The lyrics, written by Valeriano Orobón Fernández, were based on the Polish revolutionary anthem "Whirlwinds of Danger", composed by Józef Pławiński.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] Since the civil war, it has gained widespread popularity among the songs of the international left and remains in use among contemporary anarchists.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] The lyrics to the song were composed in the early 1930s by the Spanish anarchist writer Valeriano Orobón Fernández.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] The Spanish lyrics were based on a German translation of the Polish revolutionary anthem "Whirlwinds of Danger" (Polish: *Warszawianka*), the lyrics of which were originally penned in the early 1880s by Wacław Święcicki and the music composed by Józef Pławiński.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] By 1936, the song had become the official anthem of the National Confederation of Labour (CNT), an anarcho-syndicalist trade union confederation.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] It became one of the main anarchist anthems of the Spanish Civil War, together with the song "Hijos del Pueblo", and it would often be featured in the propaganda films of the CNT.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] The song was sung by the Durruti Column when it departed from Barcelona for the Aragon front.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] Composer Pablo Sorozábal reported that when his orchestra played "A las Barricadas", the anarchists and syndicalists would stand up and perform the anarchist salute, locking their hands together over their heads, while the socialists and communists remained seated.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] He likewise reported the opposite happening when his orchestra performed "The Internationale".
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] In the latter half of the 20th century, "A Las Barricades" entered the global repertoire of left-wing music, taking a place alongside other Spanish Civil War songs like "¡Ay Carmela!", the Italian partisan song "Bella ciao" and the Russian anti-fascist song "Katyusha", among others.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] The song was adopted by members of the French Confédération nationale du travail (CNT-F), headquartered on Rue des Vignoles in Paris.
[src:anti-consumerism/a-las-barricadas] It has also been covered by anarcho-punk bands, which have played renditions of it with loud electric guitars and screaming.
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] The earliest verified appearance of the term "ad creep" is in a 1996 article "Creeping Commercials: Ads Worming Way Into TV Scripts" by Steve Johnson for the *Chicago Tribune*, however it may have been coined by a subscriber to *Stay Free!* magazine, according to another source.
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] While the virtues of advertising can be debated, ad-creep often especially refers to advertising which is *invasive and coercive*, such as ads in schools, doctor's offices and hospitals, restrooms, elevators, on ATMs, on garbage cans, on vehicles, on restaurant menus, and countless other items.
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] In Steve Johnson's piece referenced above, he criticizes product placement and "creative advertising enhancements" as "one more manifestation of an environment in which the commercial assault is almost nonstop".
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] A 2017 *Daily Express* story in the UK suggests "the creeping incursion of adverts in Windows 10" has been an issue.
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] On the other hand, modern advertisers are compelled to react to changes in consumer habits.
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] As people have turned from traditional media, advertisers have not only struggled to create brand awareness, but there is also a move to "microtarget people at precisely timed moments" as well, according to an article in *Stay Free!*.
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] This is not a standard use of the term, but it is related.
[src:anti-consumerism/ad-creep] A 2017 blog post by the chief global analyst of Kantar Millward Brown, a marketing firm, notes "that average ad loads on national television in the U.S. continued to creep upwards from 10.4 minutes per hour in December 2014, to 10.9 minutes in December 2016".
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The **Adbusters Media Foundation** is a Canadian-based not-for-profit, pro-environment organization founded in 1989 by Kalle Lasn and Bill Schmalz in Vancouver, British Columbia.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] As anti-capitalist or opposed to capitalism, it publishes the reader-supported, advertising-free *Adbusters*, an activist magazine devoted to challenging consumerism.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The magazine has an international circulation peaking at 120,000 in the late 2000s with circulation of 60,000 in 2022.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Past and present contributors to the magazine include Jonathan Barnbrook, Morris Berman, Brendan Connell, Simon Critchley, David Graeber, Michael Hardt, Chris Hedges, Bill McKibben, Jim Munroe, David Orrell, Douglas Rushkoff, Matt Taibbi, Slavoj Žižek, and others.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters has launched numerous international campaigns, including Buy Nothing Day, TV Turnoff Week and Occupy Wall Street, and is known for their "subvertisements" that spoof popular advertisements.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In English, Adbusters has bi-monthly American, Canadian, Australian, UK and International editions of each issue.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters's sister organizations include *Résistance à l'Aggression Publicitaire* and *Casseurs de Pub* in France, *Adbusters Norge* in Norway, *Adbusters Sverige* in Sweden and *Culture Jammers* in Japan.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters was founded in 1989 by Kalle Lasn and Bill Schmalz, a duo of award-winning documentary filmmakers living in Vancouver.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Since the early 1980s, Lasn had been making films that explored the spiritual and cultural lessons the West could learn from the Japanese experience with capitalism.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In 1988, the *British Columbia Council of Forest Industries,* the "voice" of the logging industry, was facing tremendous public pressure from a growing environmentalist movement.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The logging industry fought back with a television ad campaign called "Forests Forever." It was an early example of greenwashing: shots of happy children, workers and animals with a kindly, trustworthy sounding narrator who assured the public that the logging industry was protecting the forest.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] According to a former Adbusters employee, "The CBC's reaction to the proposed television commercial created the real flash point for the Media Foundation.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] It seemed that Lasn and Schmaltz's commercial was too controversial to air on the CBC.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The foundation was born out of their belief that citizens do not have the same access to the information flows as corporations.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The foundation notes that concern over the flow of information goes beyond the desire to protect democratic transparency, freedom of speech or the public's access to the airwaves.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Although it supports these causes, the foundation instead situates the battle of the mind at the center of its political agenda.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Fighting to counter pro-consumerist advertising is done not as a means to an end, but as the end in itself.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] This shift in emphasis is a crucial element of mental environmentalism.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters describes itself as anti-advertising: it blames advertising for playing a central role in creating and maintaining consumer culture.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] This argument is based on the premise that the advertising industry goes to great effort and expense to associate desire and identity with commodities.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters believes that advertising has unjustly "colonized" public, discursive and psychic spaces, by appearing in movies, sports and even schools, so as to permeate modern culture.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Since *Adbusters* concludes that advertising conditions people to look to external sources, to define their own personal identities, the magazine advocates a "natural and authentic self apart from the consumer society".
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The magazine aims to provoke anti-consumerist feelings.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] By juxtaposing text and images, the magazine attempts to create a means of raising awareness and getting its message out to people that is both aesthetically pleasing and entertaining.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Activism also takes many other forms such as corporate boycotts and 'art as protest', often incorporating humor.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] This includes billboard modifications, google bombing, flash mobs and fake parking tickets for SUVs.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] A popular example of cultural jamming is the distortion of Tiger Woods' smile into the form of the Nike swoosh, calling viewers to question how they view Woods' persona as a product.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] *Adbusters* calls it "trickle up" activism, and encourages its readers to do these activities by honoring culture jamming work in the magazine.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In the September/October 2001 "Graphic Anarchy" issue, Adbusters were culture jammed themselves in a manner of speaking: they hailed the work of Swiss graphic designer Ernst Bettler as "one of the greatest design interventions on record", unaware that Bettler's story was an elaborate hoax.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] "Media Carta" is a charter challenging the corporate control of the public airwaves and means of communication.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The goal is to "make the public airwaves truly public, and not just a corporate domain." Over 30,000 people have signed the document voicing their desire to reclaim the public space.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] On 13 September 2004, Adbusters filed a lawsuit against six major Canadian television broadcasters (including CanWest Global, Bell Globemedia, CHUM Ltd., and the CBC) for refusing to air Adbusters videos in the television commercial spots that Adbusters attempted to purchase.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Most broadcasters refused the commercials, fearing the ads would upset other advertisers as well as violate business principles by "contaminating the purity of media environments designed exclusively for communicating commercial messages".
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The lawsuit claims that Adbusters' freedom of expression was unjustly limited by the refusals.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters believes the public deserves a right to be presented with viewpoints that differ from the standard.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Under Section 3 of the Broadcasting Act, television is a public space allowing ordinary citizens to possess the same rights as advertising agencies and corporations to purchase 30 seconds of airtime from major broadcasters.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] There has been talk that if Adbusters wins in Canadian court, they will file similar lawsuits against major U.S. broadcasters that also refused the advertisements.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] CNN is the only network that has allowed several of the foundation's commercials to run.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] On 3 April 2009, the British Columbia Court of Appeal unanimously overturned a BC Supreme Court ruling that had dismissed the case in February 2008.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The court granted Adbusters the ability to sue the Canadian Broadcasting Company and CanWest Global, the corporations that originally refused to air the anti-car ad "Autosaurus".
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The ruling represents a victory for Adbusters, but it is the first step of their intended goal, essentially opening the door for future legal action against the media conglomerates.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Culture jamming is the primary means through which Adbusters challenges consumerism.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The magazine was described by Joseph Heath and Andrew Potter in their book *The Rebel Sell* as "the flagship publication of the culture jamming movement." Culture jamming is heavily influenced by the Situationist International and the tactic of *détournement*.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The goal is to interrupt the normal consumerist experience in order to reveal the underlying ideology of an advertisement, media message, or consumer artifact.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters believe large corporations control mainstream media and the flow of information, and culture jamming aims to challenge this as a form of protest.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The term "jam" contains more than one meaning, including improvising, by re-situating an image or idea already in existence, and interrupting, by attempting to stop the workings of a machine.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] As already noted, the foundation's approach to culture jamming has its roots in the activities of the situationists and in particular their concept of *détournement*.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] This involves the "turning around" of received messages so that they communicate meanings at variance with their original intention.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Situationists argue that consumerism creates "a limitless artificiality", blurring the lines of reality and detracting from the essence of human experience.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The campaigns attempt to remove people from the "isolated reality of consumer comforts".
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In 2004, the foundation began selling vegan, indie shoes.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The name and logo are "open-source"; in other words, unencumbered by private trademarks.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] There are three versions of the Blackspot Sneaker.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The V1 is designed to resemble the Nike-owned Converse Chuck Taylor All-Stars (Nike bought Converse in 2003).
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The V2 is designed by Canadian shoe designer John Fluevog.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] It is made from organic hemp and recycled car tires.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] After an extensive search for anti-sweatshop manufacturers around the world, Adbusters found a small union shop in Portugal.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The sale of more than twenty-five thousand pairs through an alternative distribution network is an example of Western consumer activism marketing.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In the June 2008 cover story of *BusinessWeek Small Business Magazine*, the Blackspot campaign was among three profiled in a piece focusing on "antipreneurs." Two advertising executives were asked to review the campaign for the article's "Ask the Experts" sidebar.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Brian Martin of *Brand Connections* and Dave Weaver of TM Advertising both gave the campaign favorable reviews.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In mid-2011, Adbusters Foundation proposed a peaceful occupation of Wall Street to protest corporate influence on democracy, a growing disparity in wealth, and the absence of legal repercussions in the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] They sought to combine the symbolic location of the 2011 protests in Tahrir Square with the consensus decision making of the 2011 Spanish protests.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] On 13 July 2011 it was the staff at the magazine that created the #OCCUPYWALLSTREET hashtag on Twitter.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] While the movement was started by Adbusters, the group does not control the movement, and it has since grown worldwide.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The foundation has been criticized for having a style and form that are too similar to the media and commercial product that Adbusters attack, that its high gloss design makes the magazine too expensive, and that a style over substance approach is used to mask sub-par content.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Heath and Potter posit that the more alternative or subversive the foundation feels, the more appealing the Blackspot sneaker will become to the mainstream market.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] They believe consumers seek exclusivity and social distinction and have argued that the mainstream market seeks the very same brand of individuality that the foundation promotes; thus they see the foundation as promoting capitalist values.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The Blackspot Shoes campaign has stirred heated debate, as Adbusters admits to using the same marketing technique which it denounces other companies for using by originally purchasing much advertising space for the shoe.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Adbusters launched a legal challenge in 1995.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] A second in 2004 was against CBC, CTV, CanWest and CHUM, for refusing to air anti-consumerism commercials, therefore infringing on the staff's freedom of speech.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In one case, a CHUM representative is quoted as saying the ads "were so blatantly against television and that is our entire core business.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In March 2004, *Adbusters* was accused of antisemitism after running an article titled "Why won't anyone say they are Jewish?" The article compiled a list of neoconservative supporters within the Bush administration and marked the names of those it believed to be Jewish with a black dot.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] It questioned why, given Israel's role, the political implications of this supposed Jewish neoconservative influence on U.S. foreign policy in the Middle East were not a subject of debate.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In October 2010, Shopper's Drug Mart pulled *Adbusters* off of its shelves after a photo montage comparing the Gaza Strip to the Warsaw ghetto was featured in an article criticizing Israel's embargo of Gaza.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] The Canadian Jewish Congress campaigned to have the magazine blacklisted from bookstores, accusing *Adbusters* of trivializing the Holocaust and of antisemitism.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In response, *Adbusters* argued that the charge of antisemitism was being used to silence what it considered legitimate criticism of Israeli policies.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Some critics claim that culture jamming does little to incite real difference.
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] Others declare the movement an easy way for upper- and middle-class citizens to feel empowered by engaging in activism that bears no personal cost, such as the campaign "Buy Nothing Day".
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] These critics express a need for "resistance against the causes of capitalist exploitation, not its symptoms".
[src:anti-consumerism/adbusters] In 1999, Adbusters won the award for National Magazine of the Year in Canada.
[src:anti-consumerism/advanced-capitalism] In political philosophy, particularly Frankfurt School critical theory, **advanced capitalism** is the situation that pertains in a society in which the capitalist model has been integrated and developed deeply and extensively and for a prolonged period.
[src:anti-consumerism/advanced-capitalism] Various writers identify Antonio Gramsci as an influential early theorist of advanced capitalism, even if he did not use the term himself.
[src:anti-consumerism/advanced-capitalism] In his writings Gramsci sought to explain how capitalism had adapted to avoid the revolutionary overthrow that had seemed inevitable in the 19th century.
[src:anti-consumerism/advanced-capitalism] At the heart of his explanation was the decline of raw coercion as a tool of class power, replaced by use of civil society institutions to manipulate public ideology in the capitalists' favor.
[src:anti-consumerism/advanced-capitalism] Jürgen Habermas has been a major contributor to the analysis of advanced-capitalistic societies.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerism is concerned with the actions of individuals, as well as businesses where they act in pursuit of financial and economic goals at the expense of the perceived public good.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Commonly, anti-consumerism is connected with concern for environmental protection, anti-globalization, and animal-rights.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] *Post-consumerism*, the prioritization of well-being over material prosperity, is a related ideology.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerism originated from criticism of consumption, arguably starting with Thorstein Veblen, who, in the book *The Theory of the Leisure Class: An Economic Study of Institutions* (1899), suggested that consumerism dates from the cradle of civilization.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The term *consumerism* also denotes economic policies associated with Keynesian economics, and the belief that the free choice of consumers should dictate the economic structure of a society (cf. producerism).
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Modern political anti-consumerism developed in the 2000s.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerism can be seen as an extension of postmodern society, supporting a "decentralized culture", rejecting a hegemonic cultural imperialism of globalisation and consumption, and responding to negative impacts of consumption on the environment.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Predictors of anti-consumerist attitudes and behaviors at an individual level include concerns about environmental pollution or disruption of ecological balance, a desire to live a simple life, and a belief that a search for happiness should come from internal factors.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The diversion of libidinal energy toward the consumption of consumer products, he argues, results in an addictive cycle of consumption, leading to hyper-consumption, the exhaustion of desire, and the reign of symbolic misery.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Examples of anti-consumerist works include the book *No Logo* (2000) by Naomi Klein, and documentary films such as *The Corporation* (2003), by Mark Achbar and Jennifer Abbott, and *Surplus: Terrorized into Being Consumers* (2003), by Erik Gandini.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerist beliefs are in some cases connected with religious beliefs.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Islamic prophet Muhammad frequently endorsed simple living and anti-consumerism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerist messages are often raised in protests, including in the broader context of environmentalism and anti-corporate activism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] A notable anti-consumerist protest community is Reverend Billy and the Church of Stop Shopping.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In the context of protest art, Banksy, an influential British graffitist, painter, activist and filmmaker, has created satirical and provocative works about the consumerist society.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Examples include "Napalm", an attack on Walt Disney Pictures and McDonald's, and "Show Me the Monet", among many others.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In his 2004 book *Cut It Out*, Banksy writes, "You owe the companies nothing.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Less than nothing, you especially don't owe them any courtesy.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] They have re-arranged the world to put themselves in front of you.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Practicing anti-consumerism can mean voluntarily simplifying and minimizing one's lifestyle; this can be in efforts to exist more sustainably in a consumer culture.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] These lifestyle changes, which include choosing paper bags over plastic bags when shopping, are also in line with anti-corporate activism and green consumerism—both large contributors to the ethical market.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Degrowth, commoning and other movements aim to collectively address sustainability issues through practices and approaches that radically reduce consumption and replace consumer culture with new ethics and values.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The modern development of anti-consumerism is closely tied to the global environmental crisis, particularly the urgency surrounding climate change.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] As the world faces environmental degradation and the depletion of natural resources, anti-consumerist movements have gained momentum.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] These movements advocate for reducing overconsumption, promoting conscious consumption, and addressing waste, especially the growing plastic problem.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] A key argument for these movements is the need for both personal and systemic changes.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Many activists, such as George Monbiot, emphasize that overconsumption is a root cause of global crises like climate change, biodiversity loss, and environmental degradation.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Efforts like upcycling and reducing plastic waste are part of broader campaigns aimed at creating sustainable consumption patterns.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Moreover, critics of unchecked consumerism argue that solving these issues requires more than individual action; it also necessitates economic restructuring to lessen dependence on constant consumer spending.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] One crucial aspect of this movement is the call for "voluntary simplicity," which advocates for reducing material needs to reduce environmental impact.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] This is reflected in policies from international bodies like the United Nations, which has highlighted the importance of sustainable consumption in its development goals.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] By embracing a mindset of reducing consumption, both individuals and institutions can significantly lower emissions and resource use, addressing environmental challenges more effectively than through green technologies alone.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists believe advertising plays a huge role in human life by informing values and assumptions of the cultural system, deeming what is acceptable, and determining social standards.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] They declare that ads create a hyper-real world where commodities appear as the key to securing happiness.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists cite studies that find that individuals believe their quality of life improves in relation to social values that lie outside the capability of the marketplace.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Therefore, advertising attempts to equate the social with the material by utilizing images and slogans to link commodities with the real sources of human happiness, such as meaningful relationships.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Ads are then a detriment to society because they tell consumers that accumulating more and more possessions will bring them closer to self-actualization, or the concept of a complete and secure being.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists claim that in a consumerist society, advertisement images disempower and objectify the consumer.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] By stressing individual power, choice and desire, advertising falsely implies the control lies with the consumer.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Because anti-consumerists believe commodities supply only short-term gratification, they detract from a sustainably happy society.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Further, advertisers have resorted to new techniques of capturing attention, such as the increased speed of ads and product placements.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In this way, commercials infiltrate the consumerist society and become an inextricable part of the culture.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In a review of research on materialistic values and goals, Tim Kasser (2016) argues that the pursuit of material possessions can lead to short-term gratification at the expense of long-term well-being.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Anti-consumerists condemn advertising because it constructs a simulated world that offers fantastical escapism to consumers, rather than reflecting actual reality.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] They further argue that ads depict the interests and lifestyles of the elite as natural; cultivating a deep sense of inadequacy among viewers.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] They denounce the use of beautiful models because they glamorize the commodity beyond the reach of the average individual.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Supporters of anti-consumerism often accuse advertising of attention theft, i.e. they believe it unjustifiably invades public areas, thereby imposing itself on people who consider its presence unwanted.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] American graphic designer Sean Tejaratchi expresses his resentment of this "ad creep" in a 1999 issue of his clip art zine *Crap Hound*: "Advertising increasingly invades my environment instead of letting me come to it on my own terms when I need it...
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The most powerful and well-funded methods of mass communication in history have been used to create a one-way, unending flow of shit into my life...
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] As a classical defence pertinent in this context, Austrian economic advocates focus on the entrepreneur, promoting a productive lifestyle rather than a materialistic one wherein the individual is defined by things and not their self.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Moreover, the Austrian School dictates that the determinative estimate of goods and services motivate the demand for these commodities in order for their prices to be influenced by consumers.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Others have often hinted towards rivalry amongst consumers, in that all parties, producer and consumer alike, behave in an entrepreneurial manner; The latter's market process interpretation is assumed to have provided the entrepreneurial role only to the producer.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] This was subject to heavy debate during the Interwar era, in what was known as the socialist-calculation debate.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The status of the consumer has rarely been of any discussion in Austrian economics since.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] However, it has drawn attention to some limited degree in relation to production, with practitioners in the field having abused consumer rationality, as well as recognising their abstinence from market elucidation.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Despite its revised instances of state interventionism, adherence to the consumer theory remained abundant via the supply and demand model of Keynesianism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Paul Samuelson stated that neoclassical synthesis should have been utilised towards the extent of fiscal and monetary interventions in order for economic stabilisation and maintaining full employment, albeit emphasising that the market economy cannot solely ensure full employment.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] These are often in similar bearing with the main fundamentals of NNE, a revised edition of Neoclassical synthesis.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Developments within consumption theory of the movement were published in specialized journals.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Most of the expenditures area was addressed by consumer choice adaptations within the markets field against Keynesianism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Labour markets are often focused upon two features, opportunity cost of leisure as well as wage rate; When wage rate increases, it hints that labourers are willing to work more and it concludes with them entering the labour force.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Irrespective of the presumed incentivisation, the contrary is entirely possible, whereby workers work less and consume further leisure.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Because of these interrelations, it is reasonable to determine that wage rates and labour supply both relate positively, albeit negative for opportunity of leisure.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Nevertheless, the theory argues for gradual wage increase over time within a competitive labour market.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] This is viewed by some as an early feature of new classical theory, since it has some relation to the real business-cycle theory in technological innovation, whereby implementing automation is often similar with becoming reliant over technology for economic output.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Critics of anti-consumerism have accused anti-consumerists of opposing modernity or utilitarianism, arguing that it can lead to elitism, primarily among libertarian viewpoints, who argue that every person should decide their level of consumption independent of outside influence.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Right-wing critics see anti-consumerism as rooted in socialism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Consumerism tends to be associated with capitalism, so modern socialists tend to be anti-consumerist, with anti-consumerism described as having become "left wing common sense".
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In 1999, the libertarian magazine *Reason* attacked anti-consumerism, claiming Marxist academics were repackaging themselves as anti-consumerists.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Twitchell, a professor at the University of Florida and popular writer, referred to anti-consumerist arguments as "Marxism Lite".
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] There have also been socialist critics of anti-consumerism who see it as a form of anti-modern "reactionary socialism", and state that anti-consumerism has also been adopted by ultra-conservatives and fascists.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Rather than being incompatible with left-wing political ideologies, it has been argued that "it is not the working class that needs to be liberated from consumerism, or in other words their own material desires, but that consumerism should be liberated from capitalism".
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In her book "Authenticity Guaranteed", Sally Robinson provides a feminist critique of anti-consumerism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] She articulates that the stances of anti-consumerists reflect a hierarchical gendered framework which concerns preservation of masculinity in its purest form from the feminine social mechanisms of consumerism that curtails masculine agency and authenticity.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Citations of films such as *Fight Club* as an often anti-consumerist exemplary, according to her, presents consumerism as a crisis of masculinity in general.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] An anti-consumerist critique relies on the assumption that consumer culture is inauthentic and de-individualizing; therefore, it must also identify and delineate what constitutes the authentic and the individual.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In studies about whether anti-consumerism has been effective, it has been proven that for teenagers and young adults, the culture of media and their relationship often makes it difficult for them to reject consumerism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] *Science Daily* has a report on this, and states that it is either because they have little independence to develop their own agenda, or because they are dependent on their own consumer activities (e.g. bars, clubs and shops) to retain some independent income.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In *Fight Club*, the protagonist finds himself participating in terroristic acts against corporate society and consumer culture.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The film is regarded as one of the most widely recognizable pieces of anti-consumerist media.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The success of the book and the film comes despite the author Chuck Palahniuk publicly stating that the story is both anticonsumerist and anticommercialist.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In the novel *American Psycho* by Bret Easton Ellis, the protagonist Patrick Bateman criticizes the consumerist society of America in the 1980s of which he is a personification.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] Later on he goes on a killing spree without any consequences, suggesting that the people around him are so self-absorbed and focused on consuming that they either do not see or do not care about his acts.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In the *Pixar* movie, *WALL-E*, Earth is depicted in an apocalyptic state caused by the negative effects of human consumerism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] In the 2024 working paper *Anti-Consumerism: Stick or Carrot?* (by Iwan Bos et al.), an economic model compares the "stick" and "carrot" policies of anti-consumerism.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The "stick" policy aims to impose psychic costs (e.g., guilt) on consumers; the "carrot" policy, conversely, provides psychic benefits (e.g., pride) to non-consumers.
[src:anti-consumerism/anti-consumerism] The study found that while both approaches (weakly) reduce consumption and profits, the "carrot" policy "strictly outperforms" the "stick" policy in terms of social and consumer welfare.
